  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Ḥāl Review",
      "titleArabic": "مراجعة الحال",
      "content": [
        "The ḥāl describes the state of the subject or object during the action. It answers 'how?' or 'in what state?' and can be a word, phrase, or sentence."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Single word: جَاءَ رَاكِضًا (he came running)",
        "Prepositional phrase: جَاءَ بِسُرْعَةٍ",
        "Sentence: جَاءَ وَهُوَ يَبْكِي (he came while crying)",
        "Must agree with ṣāḥib al-ḥāl in gender/number"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "جَاءَ الطَّالِبُ مُسْرِعًا", "english": "The student came hurrying" },
        { "arabic": "رَأَيْتُهُ جَالِسًا", "english": "I saw him sitting" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Indeclinable Present Tense",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل المضارع المبني",
      "content": [
        "The present tense verb becomes indeclinable (mabnī) when attached to nūn al-niswah (feminine plural) or nūn al-tawkīd (emphatic nūn)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "With nūn al-niswah: يَكْتُبْنَ (they f. write) - mabnī 'alā sukūn",
        "With nūn al-tawkīd: لَيَكْتُبَنَّ (he will surely write) - mabnī 'alā fatḥ",
        "Heavy nūn: نَّ / Light nūn: نْ",
        "Used in oaths and emphatic statements"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "النِّسَاءُ يَكْتُبْنَ", "english": "The women write" },
        { "arabic": "وَاللهِ لأَفْعَلَنَّ", "english": "By Allah, I will surely do it" }
      ]
    }
  ],
